    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-09-21T19:29:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-09-21T19:29:00-05:00" n="626"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d626">
                <head>626. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Embassy in South Africa</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d626fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 19 SW AFR. Confidential. Drafted
                        by Ralph W. Stephan of <gloss target="#t_AF1">AF</gloss>/AFS and Runyon,
                        cleared by Campbell and <persName corresp="#p_PDH1">Popper</persName>, and
                        approved by <persName corresp="#p_PJAII1">Palmer</persName>. Sent to Cape
                        Town, and repeated to Pretoria, London, and <gloss target="#t_USUN1"
                            >USUN</gloss>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1966-09-21T20:29:00-04:00">September 21, 1966, 8:29 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>51780. Ref: a) State 30251;<note n="2" xml:id="d626fn2">Dated August 17.
                        (Ibid.)</note> b) State 45251.<note n="3" xml:id="d626fn3">Dated September
                        12. (Ibid., <gloss target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 15–1 S AFR)</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Aide memoire ref a) delivered by Asst. Sec. <persName corresp="#p_PJAII1"
                            >Palmer</persName> to <gloss target="#t_SA1">SA</gloss> Ambassador
                            <persName corresp="#p_THLT1">Taswell</persName> Sept 21.<note n="4"
                            xml:id="d626fn4">For text of the aide-memoire of September 21, see
                            Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, October 10, 1966,
                            pp. 567–568.</note> Following based on uncleared memcon:</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>
                        <p>
                            <persName corresp="#p_PJAII1">Palmer</persName> emphasized a) U.S. view
                            our aide-memoire July 15 did not represent “interference by bringing
                            unwarranted pressure bear” on <gloss target="#t_SA1">SA</gloss>; <list>
                                <label>b)</label>
                                <item>our view July 18 judgment in no way diminishes authority ICJ
                                    advisory opinions; and</item>
                                <label>c)</label>
                                <item>US will continue be guided by concern for well-being of <gloss
                                        target="#t_SWA1">SWA</gloss> inhabitants and rule of
                                    law.</item>
                            </list>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <persName corresp="#p_THLT1">Taswell</persName> persisted that a) US
                            July 15 aide-memoire constituted interference; b) USG clearly had
                            anticipated and made elaborate plans only for judgment adverse to <gloss
                                target="#t_SA1">SA</gloss> as demonstrated inter alia by time taken
                            to give US reaction to judgment and our failure provide <gloss
                                target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> copies of parallel US pre-judgment
                            demarches to Liberia and Ethiopia; c) applicants <pb facs="1108"
                                n="1060" xml:id="pg_1060"/> had withdrawn charges of oppression
                                <gloss target="#t_SWA1">SWA</gloss> clearly absolving <gloss
                                target="#t_SA1">SA</gloss> of charges; d) USG hopefully equally
                            concerned over welfare inhabitants Ethiopia and Liberia in order that
                            their standards might be brought up to those of inhabitants <gloss
                                target="#t_SWA1">SWA</gloss> and e) Gross and Ambassador <persName
                                corresp="#p_GAJ1">Goldberg</persName> at <gloss target="#t_UN1"
                                >UN</gloss> struggling cover up fact Liberia and Ethiopia had
                            withdrawn charges of <gloss target="#t_SA1">SA</gloss> oppression <gloss
                                target="#t_SWA1">SWA</gloss>.</p>
                    </item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PJAII1">Palmer</persName> a) maintained view USG
                        demarche appropriate and not interference; b) emphasized US demarches to
                            <gloss target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss>, Ethiopia and Liberia strictly
                        matter US diplomatic relations with individual countries; <gloss
                            target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> publicly referred to our approach to it;
                        other two have not done so; US could not have reacted complex judgment on
                        merits any faster than to judgment rendered; c) emphasized narrowness of
                        issue (jurisdiction, not merits) decided by <gloss target="#t_ICJ1"
                            >ICJ</gloss> on July 18 and d) said he could not accept <persName
                            corresp="#p_THLT1">Taswell</persName>’s inappropriate remark re
                        Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_GAJ1">Goldberg</persName> suggesting if
                            <gloss target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> had any question it would be one to
                        be taken up by <gloss target="#t_SA1">SA</gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_UN1">UN</gloss> Del with Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_GAJ1">Goldberg</persName>.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PJAII1">Palmer</persName> said <gloss target="#t_SAG1"
                            >SAG</gloss> would do service to all by carrying out continuing
                        obligations regarding <gloss target="#t_SWA1">SWA</gloss> and he hoped
                            <gloss target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> would take careful account of
                        present <gloss target="#t_UNGA1">UNGA</gloss> which could prove unusually
                        difficult one for <gloss target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss>.</item>
                    <label>6.</label>
                    <item>Interesting <persName corresp="#p_THLT1">Taswell</persName> put more
                        emphasis on shift in applicants’ contention before <gloss target="#t_ICJ1"
                            >ICJ</gloss> than on any implications from obiter dicta in judgment in
                        seeking paint judgment as vindication of <gloss target="#t_SAG1"
                        >SAG</gloss>.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Ball</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
